Respiratory Virus Situation Report (AZ, NM, UT)

COVID

The current COVID epidemic trend is not estimated for Utah, is not changing for Arizona, and is growing for New Mexico. The weekly percentage of ED visits diagnosed with COVID is very low for Utah, Arizona, and New Mexico. Hospital admissions for COVID are currently decreasing in Arizona, increasing in New Mexico, and stable in Utah.

INFLUENZA

The current flu epidemic trend is not estimated for Utah, but is growing for Arizona and New Mexico. The weekly percentage of ED visits diagnosed with flu is not estimated for Utah but is very low for Arizona and New Mexico. Hospital admissions for flu are currently stable in Utah and increasing in New Mexico and in Utah.

RSV

No state-level estimates are currently available for RSV. RSV burden remains low across Arizona, New Mexico, and Utah.

About this report:

  • This report describes recent state-level trends in respiratory virus activity in Arizona, New Mexico, and Utah. It presents data on three respiratory viral diseases: COVID-19, influenza (flu), and respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). Trends in emergency department visits are based on National Syndromic Surveillance Program (NSSP) data and provide estimates of how much symptomatic illness each virus is causing. Hospitalization trends are drawn from National Healthcare Safety Network (NHSN) data and estimate the burden of severe disease and impact on the healthcare system caused by each virus. Emergency department visit and hospitalization data from the previous year are also shown for comparison.
    • For more information related to scenario projections for COVID, flu, and RSV, comparing outbreak trajectories under different assumptions around key features of interventions, pathogens, and populations that drive disease dynamics, visit the ScenarioModelingHub.
    • For more information on current and past season vaccination coverage for each pathogen, visit COVIDVaxView, FluVaxView, or RSVVaxView.
